07879nam a22009495i 9780812297799DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780812297799  a(DE-B1597)573134  a(OCoLC)1243547594  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aB2798b.K368 2021 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a19322300aKant and the Possibility of Progress :bFrom Modern Hopes to Postmodern Anxieties /ced. by Samuel Stoner, Samuel A. Stoner, Paul T. Wilford. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b2  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Modernity and Postmodernity: Our Temporal Orientation -- tPART I. KANT ON PROGRESS -- tChapter 1. Kant on Individual Moral Progress -- tChapter 2. Should We Believe in Moral Progress? -- tChapter 3. Respect, Moral Progress, and Imperfect Duty -- tChapter 4. Loneliness and Ambiguity in Kant’s Philosophy of History -- tChapter 5. Kant’s Organic Religion: God, Teleology, and Progress in the Third Critique -- tChapter 6. Realizing the Ethical Community: Kant’s Religion and the Reformation of Culture -- tChapter 7. Kant as Soothsayer: The Problem of Progress and the “Sign” of History -- tPART II. PROGRESS AFTER KANT -- tChapter 8. History, Progress, and Autonomy: Kant, Herder, and After -- tChapter 9. Language, Embodiment, and the Supersensuous in Fichte’s Addresses to the German Nation -- tChapter 10. Hegel on the Conceptual Form of Philosophical History -- tChapter 11. Relocating the Highest Good: Kierkegaard on God, Virtue, and (This- Worldly) Happiness -- tChapter 12. Kant and Benjamin on Hope, History, and the Task of Interpretation -- tChapter 13. The Curious Fate of the Idea of Progress -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImmanuel Kant (1724-1804) transformed the philosophical, cultural, and religious landscape of modern Europe. Emphasizing the priority of practical reason and moral autonomy, Kant's radically original account of human subjectivity announced new ethical imperatives and engendered new political hopes. This collection of essays investigates the centrality of progress to Kant's philosophical project and the contested legacy of Kant's faith in reason's capacity to advance not only our scientific comprehension and technological prowess, but also our moral, political, and religious lives. Accordingly, the first half of the volume explores the many facets of Kant's thinking about progress, while the remaining essays each focus on one or two thinkers who play a crucial role in post-Kantian German philosophy: J. G. Herder (1744-1803), J. G. Fichte (1762-1814), G. W. F. Hegel (1770-1831), Søren Kierkegaard (1813-1855), Friedrich Nietzsche (1844-1900), Walter Benjamin (1892-1940), and Martin Heidegger (1889-1976). This two-part structure reflects the central thesis of the volume that Kant inaugurates a distinctive theoretical tradition in which human historicity is central to political philosophy.By exploring the origins and metamorphoses of this tremendously influential tradition, the volume offers a timely perspective on fundamental questions in an age increasingly suspicious of the Enlightenment's promise of universal rational progress. It aims to help us face three sets of questions: (1) Do we still believe in the possibility of progress? If we do, on what grounds? If we do not, why have we lost the hope for a better future that animated previous generations? (2) Is the belief in progress necessary for the maintenance of today's liberal democratic order? Does a cosmopolitan vision of politics ultimately depend on a faith in humanity's gradual, asymptotic realization of that lofty aim? (3) And, if we no longer believe in progress, can we dispense with hope without succumbing to despair?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPhilosophy and civilization. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aProgress. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aPhilosophy.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aAlznauer, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmeriks, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemp, Ryan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeld Shell, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoran, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPippin, Robert B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSensen, Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpeight, C. Allen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStoner, Samuel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStoner, Samuel A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStoner, Samuel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTimmermann, Jens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVelkley, Richard L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilford, Paul T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilford, Paul T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZuckert, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z